<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-112-396  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 112 396.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  March 13 1989 n408 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Legislation proposed for copyright loophole.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Peterson, Stacey.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Congress is considering legislation to close a loophole in the USCopyright Act by specifying that the states and their instruments,such as colleges and universities, are included under the law.andO;Current law permits states to violate federal copyright lawwithout recourse for the injured party.andP;  Rep Robert Kastenmeier,D-WI, and Carlos Moorhead, R-CA, are proposing the CopyrightRemedy Clarification Act.andP;  Sen Dennis DeConcini, D-AR, is authorof a similar bill in the Senate.andP;  The courts have said the law isnot explicit in its application to the states and the USConstitution's eleventh amendment protects states from being suedunder federal law unless the US Congress takes specific action.andP;  Arecent ruling in a BV Engineering suit against the University ofCalifornia, Los Angeles, is on appeal to the US Supreme Court.andO;Another case testing Congress' right to abrogate states' immunityis also pending before the Supreme Court.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CopyrightGovernment RegulationUnited States. CongressLegal IssuesColleges and UniversitiesState GovernmentLegislation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>